{"title_page": "Homicide of Richard Oland", "text_new": "The '''homicide of Richard Oland''' occurred on July 7, 2011, when 69-year-old [[Canada|Canadian]] businessman [[Richard Oland]], previously a vice-president with [[Moosehead Brewery]], was bludgeoned to death in his office on Canterbury Street in [[Saint John, New Brunswick|Saint John]], [[New Brunswick]].<ref name=\"car shoes bag\">{{Cite web|title = Dennis Oland's car, shoes, bag all tested negative for blood, jury hears|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/oland-murder-trial-mark-smith-1.3260262|website = www.cbc.ca|access-date = 2016-02-19}}</ref> Oland's son, Dennis, came under suspicion for the killing and was officially charged with [[second degree murder]].<ref name=\"huffpo\">{{cite news|last1=Bissett|first1=Kevin|title=Dennis Oland Charged In Father's Death|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2013/11/13/dennis-oland-murder_n_4266411.html|accessdate=5 July 2014|agency=Associated Press|publisher=Huffington Post|date=2013-11-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Dennis Oland charged with 2nd-degree murder in dad's death|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/dennis-oland-charged-with-2nd-degree-murder-in-dad-s-death-1.2424736|website = www.cbc.ca|access-date = 2016-02-19}}</ref> Dennis Oland's first trial, the longest and most expensive trial in the history of Saint John,<ref name=\"by storm\">{{Cite web|title = How the Oland family murder trial took New Brunswick by storm|url = http://www.macleans.ca/news/canada/the-oland-murder-trial-that-took-new-brunswick-by-storm/|website = Macleans.ca|access-date = 2016-02-19|language = en-US}}</ref> ended with his conviction on December 19, 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Dennis Oland found guilty of second-degree murder|url = https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/dennis-oland-found-guilty-in-murder-of-his-father/article27883485/|website = The Globe and Mail|access-date = 2016-02-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = 'Family tragedy of Shakespearean proportions': Oland gets life for murder|url = http://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/family-tragedy-of-shakespearean-proportions-oland-gets-life-for-murder-1.2773467?autoPlay=true|website = Atlantic|access-date = 2016-02-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Supporters line up as Dennis Oland faces sentencing for murder - Macleans.ca|url = http://www.macleans.ca/news/dennis-oland-faces-sentencing-for-second-degree-murder-in-fathers-death/|website = Macleans.ca|access-date = 2016-02-19|language = en-US}}</ref> Throughout the high-profile court case, intimate details about the private lives of the entire Oland family were revealed.<ref name=\"living hell\">{{Cite web|title = Dennis Oland's mother, Connie, shares 'living hell'|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/dennis-oland-mother-connie-murder-1.3449295|website = www.cbc.ca|access-date = 2016-02-19}}</ref>\n\nDennis Oland was sentenced to [[life imprisonment|life in prison]], with a possibility of [[parole]] in ten years, as recommended by the jury.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/dennis-oland-sentencing-murder-1.3435552|title=Dennis Oland gets life in prison for killing father, Richard Oland|date=11 February 2016|publisher=}}</ref> His lawyers immediately began the [[appeal]]s process, seeking the appellate judges to either overturn the guilty verdict, order a new trial, or enter a full [[acquittal]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = No bail for Dennis Oland as he waits to appeal conviction in father's murder|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/dennis-oland-bail-murder-appeal-1.3450016|website = www.cbc.ca|access-date = 2016-02-19}}</ref> The appeal was successful, and Dennis's conviction was overturned on October 24, 2016. On July 19, 2019, he was found not guilty on retrial.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/dennis-oland-murder-trial-decision-verdict-1.5215559 |title=Dennis Oland not guilty of murder in retrial over 2011 death of multimillionaire father |date= 19 July 2019 |website= CBC News |publisher= CBC |access-date=19 July 2019 |quote= N.B. Court of Queen's Bench Justice Morrison had been deliberating for 10 weeks in 2nd-degree murder trial}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nRichard Oland was the second born son to [[Philip Oland]], chairman and CEO of [[Moosehead Breweries]], and Mary Oland.<ref name=\"Dynasty Macleans\">{{Cite web|title = Murder and a Maritime dynasty: The Dick Oland case - Macleans.ca|url = http://www.macleans.ca/economy/business/murder-and-a-maritime-dynasty-the-dick-oland-case/|website = Macleans.ca|access-date = 2016-02-19|language = en-US}}</ref> Richard and his older brother Derek were born and reared in [[Rothesay, New Brunswick|Rothesay]], [[New Brunswick]], a suburb of [[Saint John, New Brunswick|Saint John]]. Families living within Rothesay, such as the Olands, the [[Irving Oil|Irvings]], and the [[Molasses|Crosbys]], are considered \"old money,\" claiming some of Canada's highest incomes per capita.<ref name=\"Dynasty Macleans\" /> Richard attended Rothesay Collegiate School, Regiopolis College, and the University of New Brunswick, obtaining a certificate of brewing technology.<ref name=\"Dynasty Macleans\" /><ref name=\"Blood, Beer\">{{Cite web|title = Blood, Beer, and the Maritime Rumour Mill: The Dennis Oland Murder Trial   {{!}} VICE {{!}} Canada|url = https://www.vice.com/en_ca/read/blood-beer-and-the-small-town-rumour-mill-the-dennis-oland-murder-trial|website = VICE|access-date = 2016-02-19|language = en-ca}}</ref><ref name=\"funeral home\">{{Cite web|title = Richard Henry Oland - Brenan's Funeral Homes & Crematorium|url = http://www.brenansfh.com/obituaries/63451|website = Brenan's Funeral Homes & Crematorium|access-date = 2016-02-23}}</ref> Richard wed Constance \"Connie\" Connell in 1965,<ref name=\"living hell\" /> and fathered three children: Elizabeth, Jacequeline, and Dennis.<ref name=\"funeral home\" />\n\nBy 1980, Richard, then a vice-president of Moosehead Breweries, vied with Derek for leadership of the company in a public and legal feud. Their father Philip decided to select Derek to succeed him, resulting in Richard leaving the company in 1981.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.macleans.ca/economy/business/murder-and-a-maritime-dynasty-the-dick-oland-case/ |title=Murder and a Maritime dynasty: The Dick Oland case |last=K\u00f6hler |first=Nicholas |date=13 November 2013 |website=Macleans |publisher=Rogers Media |access-date=23 January 2017 |quote=\u201cThe younger one wanted to be president and he hadn\u2019t the experience,\u201d P.W. once told the Financial Post Magazine coolly.}}</ref> Starting from scratch, Richard found a niche in the Saint John business community with his development of three major enterprises - Kinghurst Estates Limited, Brookville Transport Limited, and the [[investment company|investment firm]] Far End Corporation.<ref name=\"living hell\" /> He became an accomplished businessman, amassing many awards and a fortune of nearly [[Canadian dollar|CA$]]37 million.<ref name=\"opens with details\">{{Cite web|title = Oland murder trial opens with details of beating, accused\u2019s financial woes|url = https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/dennis-olands-second-degree-murder-trial-opens-in-new-brunswick/article26377714/|website = The Globe and Mail|access-date = 2016-02-23}}</ref> Oland was also in charge of organizing the 1985 Canada Summer Games.<ref name=\"living hell\"/>\n\nRichard made Far End Corporation's premises his primary office space.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.atlanticbusinessmagazine.net/article/spilled-secrets-the-richard-oland-murder-mystery/ |title=Spilled secrets: the Richard Oland murder mystery |last=Kimber |first=Stephen |date=19 December 2013 |website=Atlantic Business Magazine |publisher=Atlantic Business Magazine |access-date=23 January 2017 |quote=52 Canterbury Street, a refurbished 19th century, three storey, red-brick office building in the heart of historic ... Saint John}}</ref> Located at 52 Canterbury Street in the historic Uptown district of Saint John, the second floor office space was rented from building owner John Ainsworth. Ainsworth operated his own business, Printing Plus, from the first floor of the building, and rented out the third floor to local bands to practice after office hours ended for the day.<ref name=\"mentioned\">{{Cite web|title = How a city councillor ended up being mentioned in the Oland trial|url = https://www.telegraphjournal.com/telegraph-journal/story/45817628/how-a-city-councillor|website = Telegraph-Journal|access-date = 2016-02-19}}</ref> The morning of July 7, 2011, Richard was discovered dead in his office.\n\n== Crime scene ==\nOn July 7, 2011, the body of Richard Oland was discovered lying face down in a pool of blood in his office by his personal assistant, Maureen Adamson.<ref name=\"survived minutes\">{{Cite web|title = Richard Oland survived only 'minutes,' murder trial hears|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/dennis-oland-richard-survived-pathologist-1.3264289|website = www.cbc.ca|access-date = 2016-02-19}}</ref> Sgt. Mark Smith testified that Richard's office was \"one of the bloodiest crime scenes of his career, with the most blows to a victim.\"<ref name=\"car shoes bag\"/> The forensic pathologist, Dr. Ather Naseemuddin, counted forty-five wounds to Richard's hands, neck, and head, during autopsy.<ref name=\"survived minutes\" /><!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Richard Oland's lifeless body.jpg|thumb|274x274px|Richard Oland's body at the crime scene.]] --> Six of these wounds were found on Richard's hands, likely due to Richard trying to protect himself from his attacker.<ref name=\"survived minutes\" /> These [[defensive wound]]s led to over thirty hair and fibre exhibits to be seized at [[autopsy]] for forensic examination, including three hairs found inside Richard's hands and tissue samples from under Richard's fingernails.<ref name=\"Defence evidence\">{{Cite web|title = Defence questions police handling of evidence at Oland trial|url = http://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/defence-questions-police-handling-of-evidence-at-oland-trial-1.2660319|website = Atlantic|access-date = 2016-02-23}}</ref> The hairs could not be tested for DNA as they were lacking a root, and only Richard's DNA was found underneath his fingernails.<ref name=\"Defence evidence\" /><ref name=\"R v Oland 2013\">R. v. Oland, [2013] NBJ 457 (NB CA).</ref>\n\nThe attack continued after Richard was defenseless on the floor.<ref name=\"survived minutes\" /> His skull had suffered catastrophic damage; the bones of his eyesockets were \"like a cracked egg shell,\" possibly from him falling face-first into the floor,<ref name=\"survived minutes\" /> and a concave area spanning 10&nbsp;cm in length, 7&nbsp;cm across, and 2&nbsp;cm deep was discovered at autopsy.<ref name=\"R v Oland 2013\" /> Portions of brain matter were found on Richard's back.<ref name=\"Unanswered\">{{Cite web|title = Questions remain unanswered after Dennis Oland\u2019s trial|url = https://www.telegraphjournal.com/telegraph-journal/story/45891217/questions-remain-unanswered-after|website = Telegraph-Journal|access-date = 2016-02-22}}</ref>\n\nThe attack had left Richard's blood on every single wall of his office.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Dennis Oland murder trial: Oct. 19|url = http://live.cbc.ca/Event/Dennis_Oland_murder_trial_Oct_19?Page=0|website = CBC News|access-date = 2016-02-19}}</ref> Blood spatter was seen on his desk, computer, chair, filing cabinets, and on an empty pizza box in the garbage can.<ref name=\"survived minutes\" /> Blood had also soaked through three layers of flooring, permeating the ceiling of the office below.<ref name=\"Blood, Beer\" /><ref>{{Cite web|title = Trial Hears Dennis Oland Appointed President Of Holding Company After Father's Death {{!}} Country 94 - Saint John, New Brunswick's Best Country Music|url = http://www.country94.ca/news/744206911/trial-hears-dennis-oland-appointed-president-holding-company-after-fathers-death|website = www.country94.ca|access-date = 2016-02-19}}</ref> Police analysts testified \"the person who created these injuries would have significant bloodstains/spatter on their person and would be expected to transfer blood stains to the surfaces of other objects the person came in contact with.\"<ref name=\"R v Oland 2015\">R. v. Oland, [2015] NBJ 312 (NB CA).</ref> Forensic analysts noted the blood pooling on the floor around Richard may not have occurred until after the attacker left the office, explaining why the scene contained few \"transfer stains\" and only one footprint that was never connected to a suspect.<ref name=\"ought to have\">{{Cite web|title = Officers ought to have known how to protect Oland crime scene, trial hears|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/oland-murder-trial-bathroom-1.3258375|website = www.cbc.ca|access-date = 2016-02-22}}</ref>\n\nDr. Matthew Bowes, the physician who reviewed Dr. Nasseemuddin's autopsy report, believed Richard was alive for the duration of the attack.<ref name=\"alive for duration\">{{Cite news|title = Evidence claims Oland was alive for duration of attack.|last = Landry|first = Mike|publisher = New Brunswick Telegraph Journal}}</ref> Both Naseemuddin and Bowes believed he only survived the attack for five to ten minutes<ref name=\"Graphic\">{{Cite web|title = Graphic testimony of Richard Oland\u2019s autopsy heard by Saint John jury Friday|url = http://globalnews.ca/news/2269224/graphic-testimony-of-richard-olands-autopsy-heard-by-saint-john-jury-friday/|website = Global News|access-date = 2016-02-22|first = Heide|last = Pearson}}</ref> but was alive for all of his injuries.<ref name=\"alive for duration\" /> Some injuries were believed to have been caused by a sharp edged weapon, while other injuries were caused by blunt force,<ref name=\"survived minutes\" /> indicating that either Richard was killed by a weapon with two different edges or two weapons were used.<ref name=\"R v Oland 2015\" /> Bowes raised the possibility that a combat knife could have been a weapon.<ref name=\"combat knife\">{{Cite news|title = Combat knife could have been used to kill Oland: expert.|last = Landry|first = Mike|date = Feb 20, 2016|publisher = Telegraph Journal}}</ref> Sgt. Mike King testified that he suspected a roofer's [[hatchet]] to be a weapon.<ref name=\"combat knife\" /> Constable Stephen Davidson believed a weapon could have been a drywall hammer.<ref name=\"drywall hammer\">{{Cite web|title = Dennis Oland murder trial hears suspected weapon was drywall hammer|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/oland-murder-weapon-drywall-hammer-1.3283461|website = www.cbc.ca|access-date = 2016-02-22}}</ref>  No weapons were found at the crime scene, and no weapons were entered as evidence at trial.<ref name=\"drywall hammer\" />\n\nThe trial revealed that members of the Saint John Police Force had failed to protect the crime scene from contamination. Police used the office bathroom, where  blood belonging to the son of Richard's financial manager was later discovered, for two days before the bathroom was tested for evidence.<ref name=\"ought to have\" /> There was a backdoor near where Richard's body was found, leading to an alleyway that could have been an exit.<ref>{{cite book |last=Marquis |first=Greg |date=2016 |title=Truth & Honour. The Death of Richard Oland and the Trial of Dennis Oland. |url=https://www.nimbus.ca/store/truth-and-honour.html?___SID=U |location=Halifax |publisher=Nimbus Publishing |page=22 |isbn=978-1-77108-425-3}}</ref> Police went in and out the main door, without gloves, for nearly a week before anyone noticed they should have tested it for fingerprints.<ref name=\"ought to have\" /> The footprint discovered by the forensics team had to be compared against police footwear, as several police officers, including Deputy Chief Glen McCloskey, walked through the crime scene unauthorized and without protective gear.<ref name=\"ought to have\" /><ref name=\"deputy denies\">{{Cite web|title = Deputy chief denies suggesting officer lie about Richard Oland crime scene|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/dennis-oland-trial-king-police-1.3270115|website = www.cbc.ca|access-date = 2016-02-22}}</ref> McCloskey was later accused of suggesting that other officers [[perjury|lie under oath]] about his presence at the crime scene,<ref name=\"deputy denies\" /> and Saint John Police is currently under investigation by the New Brunswick Police Commission for [[police corruption|corruption]] and a potential cover-up.<ref name=\"Blood, Beer\" /><ref>{{Cite web|title = Saint John police under investigation for how they handled Oland murder|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/oland-investigation-police-commission-1.3376852|website = www.cbc.ca|access-date = 2016-02-22}}</ref>\n\n== Police interviews ==\n\nShortly after being notified of the death, members of the Oland family, including Richard's wife Connie Oland, daughters Lisa Bustin and Jacqueline Walsh, and son Dennis Oland, arrived at the police station to give interviews and formal statements.<ref name=\"living hell\" />\n\nConnie said that on July 6, 2011, she and Richard were both at home until Richard received a call from Maureen Adamson at 9:50 am, reminding him of an appointment in his office with two insurance brokers at 10:00 am.<ref name=\"Order to Rogers\">{{Cite web|url = http://http-server.carleton.ca/~dmckie/Oland%20Production%20Orders.pdf|title = Production Order to Rogers Communications|date = July 9, 2011|publisher = Court of Queen's Bench of New Brunswick|last = Humphrey|first = Stacey}}</ref> Richard then left home for the office, and that was the last time Connie spoke with him. Connie said it was not uncommon for Richard not to return to their residence at night.<ref name=\"Order to Rogers\" />\n\nLisa Bustin, Dennis's sister, was interviewed alone. Bustin said that her father could have had anyone as an enemy, as he was \"a hard-nosed businessman--pure business--and if you worked hard you would get his respect.\"<ref name=\"shed new light\">{{Cite web\n| url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/documents-shed-new-light-on-oland-murder-investigation-1.1699119\n| title = Documents shed new light on Oland murder investigation\n| website = www.cbc.ca\n| access-date = 2016-02-25\n}}</ref>\n\nDennis Oland's interview lasted over five hours and was separate from those of other family members.<ref name=\"living hell\" /> Video footage showed Dennis providing Cst. Stephen Davidson with a written and verbal account of his activities for the day prior, July 6, 2011. He believed that his father had high expectations of him, but that Dennis was not meeting those expectations.\n\nDavidson told Dennis that cameras could verify whether or not he was telling the truth about his presence at his father's office, and asked Dennis what clothing he had worn the day before. Dennis said he was wearing \"these pants, these shoes, a blue dress shirt, and a navy blazer.\"<ref name=\"RAW\">{{Cite web|title = RAW: Dennis Oland's police statement|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/raw-dennis-oland-s-police-statement-1.3283018|website = www.cbc.ca|access-date = 2016-02-19}}</ref>\n\nAt the half-way mark on the video footage, Davidson informed Dennis that he was the primary suspect in his father Richard Oland's murder.<ref name=\"video jury\">{{Cite web|title = Police video jury didn't see shows Dennis Oland being pressured to admit killing father|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/dennis-oland-police-murder-confession-1.3436687|website = www.cbc.ca|access-date = 2016-02-22}}</ref> Davidson read Dennis his rights, and Dennis phoned attorney Bill Teed, who told Dennis to stop talking to police.<ref name=\"video jury\" /> Davidson said \"there is absolutely no question in my mind that you did this, and I want to know why,\" and told Dennis that his opportunity to speak with a lawyer was past. Dennis repeated that he did not murder his father.<ref name=\"video jury\" />\n\nPolice allowed Dennis to leave just after 11:00pm without making an effort to seize the clothes Dennis said he had worn the day before.<ref name=\"Unanswered\" />\n\nRobert McFadden, in his interview, conducted by Cst. Stephen Davidson,<ref name=\"Order to Rogers\" /> said he had left the office at 5:30 pm with his son, Galen McFadden, as was usual.<ref name=\"Order to Rogers\" /> Robert McFadden said his job was to manage Richard's finances, and that Richard had asked that a trust fund be set up for his heirs.<ref name=\"instructions\">{{Cite web|url = http://s3.documentcloud.org/documents/2648059/R-v-Oland-Final-Instructions-Jury-s-Written.txt|title = Judge Walsh's charge to the jury in R. v. Oland|date = December 2015|access-date = February 15, 2016|publisher = The Court of Queen's Bench of New Brunswick|last = Walsh|first = John J.}}</ref> After Richard's death, McFadden said he would run two of Richard's three companies (Kingshurt Estate Ltd and Far End Corporation).<ref name=\"instructions\" /><ref>{{Cite web\n| url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/dennis-oland-murder-director-companies-1.3453441\n| title = Dennis Oland could co-direct murdered father's companies from behind bars\n| website = www.cbc.ca\n| access-date = 2016-02-25\n}}</ref>\n\nMcFadden said that upon Connie's death, the trust would be dissolved, and the remaining assets would be distributed to Richard's three children, Dennis Oland, Jacqueline Walsh, and Lisa Bustin.<ref name=\"instructions\" /> He said that after Connie's death, Dennis's portion of his inheritance would be reduced by $538,000, with $269,000 going to each of Dennis's sisters, covering the expenses of his divorce, which had been paid for by Richard, and allowing Dennis to retain the family home.<ref name=\"instructions\" />\n\nRobert McFadden and Maureen Adamson testified that Richard did not leave the office between arriving in the morning and Maureen leaving at 5:45 PM, and that Richard was adamant that alcohol not be kept in the office.<ref name=\"survived minutes\" /><ref name=\"trial nov 3\">{{Cite web|title = Dennis Oland's second-degree murder trial: Nov. 3|url = http://live.cbc.ca/Event/Dennis_Olands_second-degree_murder_trial_Nov_3?Page=0|website = CBC News|access-date = 2016-02-20}}</ref> Toxicology reports from the medical examiner indicate that Richard had some alcohol in his blood.<ref name=\"Graphic\" />\n\n== Suspects ==\nTwo weeks after the death, police said that they were convinced Richard was murdered by someone he knew.<ref name=\"became suspect\">{{Cite web|title = Dennis Oland became suspect in father's murder same day body was found|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/dennis-oland-murder-statement-1.3281699|website = www.cbc.ca|access-date = 2016-02-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Oland investigation puts Saint John in eerie calm|url = https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/oland-investigation-puts-saint-john-in-eerie-calm/article557442/|website = The Globe and Mail|access-date = 2016-02-23}}</ref>\n\nSince July 2011, the McFaddens have shared information to advance the investigation. In 2012, nearly a year after the murder, Galen McFadden gave a sample of his DNA.<ref name=\"ought to have\" /> Robert McFadden declined to give a DNA sample.<ref name=\"will insurance\">{{Cite web\n| url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/richard-oland-will-insurance-mcfadden-1.3301617\n| title = Richard Oland was considering changing will, life insurance, jury hears\n| website = www.cbc.ca\n| access-date = 2016-02-25\n}}</ref> Forensic testing in 2012 reveal that blood matching the DNA profile of Galen McFadden was found on the curtains of Richard's office,<ref name=\"blood stain expert\">{{Cite web|title = Blood stain expert continues testimony at Oland murder trial|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/dennis-oland-second-degree-murder-oct-16-1.3274034|website = www.cbc.ca|access-date = 2016-02-22}}</ref> in the bathroom sink, and on a paper towel in the bathroom garbage can.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Dennis Oland second-degree murder trial: Nov. 24|url = http://live.cbc.ca/Event/Dennis_Oland_second-degree_murder_trial_Nov_24?Page=2|website = CBC News|access-date = 2016-02-22}}</ref> One year after Galen's blood was found at the crime scene, officers covertly obtained Robert McFadden's DNA from a straw at a restaurant.<ref name=\"will insurance\" /> The police forensics unit concluded the three areas where Galen's blood was found were unrelated to Richard's murder.  No results concerning Robert's DNA were released.\n\n== Forensic analysis ==\nSgt. Mark Smith, head of the forensics unit of the Saint John Police Force, said he spent three days following the July 14, 2011 search of Dennis's home doing a \"very thorough search\" of Dennis's car.<ref name=\"car shoes bag\" />  Ten different areas of the car were swabbed, including the driver's side door inside latch and handle, the trunk release button, the headlight switch, signal light switch, the steering wheel, the emergency brake, and seats of the car.<ref name=\"live.cbc.ca\">{{Cite web\n| url = http://live.cbc.ca/Event/Dennis_Olands_second-degree_murder_trial_Oct_6\n| title = Dennis Oland's second-degree murder trial: Oct. 6\n| website = ScribbleLive Embed\n| access-date = 2016-02-26\n}}</ref> The swabs were sent away on July 21, 2011, for forensic testing at the RCMP crime lab in Nova Scotia, but no blood or DNA was detected through these tests, either.<ref name=\"R v Oland 2015\" /><ref name=\"live.cbc.ca\"/>\n\nSmith did not find blood or DNA in the laces, stitching, or tread of any of the six pairs of shoes seized from Dennis's home, nor in the red reusable grocery bag Dennis had used to carry genealogy books into Richard's office on July 6, 2011.<ref name=\"car shoes bag\" /> Smith didn't find any blood in the keys of Dennis's Blackberry cell phone, and Richard's DNA was not found anywhere on the phone.<ref name=\"car shoes bag\" />\n\nFor four hours on November 9, 2011, and 1 hour on November 17, 2011, Cst. David MacDonald visually inspected Dennis's brown jacket for blood, identifying 5 \"reddish\" spots, invisible to the naked eye, that required testing by the RCMP forensics lab in Nova Scotia.<ref name=\"jacket focus\">{{Cite web|title = Blood on Dennis Oland's jacket focus of murder trial today|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/richard-oland-murder-trial-1.3277845|website = www.cbc.ca|access-date = 2016-02-23}}</ref> The jacket is sent to the RCMP lab on November 25, 2011, after the warrant for police seizure of the jacket had expired. Four spots on the jacket are confirmed to be blood that matches Richard's DNA - two spots on the outside right sleeve of the jacket, one spot on the outside upper left chest of the jacket, and one spot on the outside back bottom hem near the center of the jacket.<ref name=\"officer gloves\">{{Cite web|title = Dennis Oland's brown jacket was handled by officer without gloves|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/oland-trial-jacket-blood-1.3299712|website = www.cbc.ca|access-date = 2016-02-23}}</ref>\n\n==Charges==\nIn November 2013 Dennis Oland was charged with [[Murder|second degree murder]] for the death of his father. Police stated that no one else would be charged.<ref name=huffpo /> Dennis entered a plea of \"not guilty.\" On November 18, 2013, Justice Hugh McLellan of the New Brunswick Court of Queen's Bench granted Dennis bail on a $50,000 surety, paid by Dennis's uncle (Richard's brother) Derek Oland, the executive chairman of Moosehead Breweries.<ref name=\"R v Oland 2013\" /><ref>{{Cite web\n| url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/dennis-oland-murder-appeal-1.3398445\n| title = Dennis Oland, N.B. man found guilty of murdering multimillionaire father, appeals conviction\n| website = www.cbc.ca\n| access-date = 2016-02-26\n}}</ref> Dennis was also ordered to surrender his passport and advise the [[Saint John Police]] if he planned to travel outside of the province.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/dennis-oland-charged-with-murder-in-fathers-death-granted-bail/article15487595/|title=Dennis Oland, charged with murder in father\u2019s death, granted bail|work=The Globe and Mail}}</ref>\n\n== Preliminary inquiry ==\nProvincial court Judge Ronald LeBlanc presided over the preliminary inquiry on December 12, 2014.<ref name=\"set to begin\">{{Cite web\n| url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/dennis-oland-murder-trial-set-to-begin-in-september-take-65-days-1.2936943\n| title = Dennis Oland murder trial set to begin in September, take 65 days\n| website = www.cbc.ca\n| access-date = 2016-02-26\n}}</ref> He referred to the inquiry as a \"screening mechanism\" to review all of the evidence and rule whether or not he felt the case against Dennis Oland was strong enough to warrant a trial. The preliminary inquiry ultimately spanned 37 days.<ref name=\"Unanswered\" /><ref name=\"set to begin\" />\n\nCrown Prosecutor John Henheffer said that Dennis may have had a financial [[b:Canadian Criminal Evidence|motive]] to murder his father, and that Dennis may have asked his father for more money but was denied by Richard, triggering Dennis's murderous rage.<ref name=\"Unanswered\" />\n\nLeBlanc told the Crown they had \"failed to establish a reason for Dennis Oland to kill his father\" as Connie, Richard's wife, received the $37 million inheritance, not Dennis.<ref name=\"Unanswered\" /> He also said the Crown had no evidence showing that Dennis asked for money or that being denied money would cause Dennis to be violent against his father.<ref name=\"Unanswered\" />\n\nCell phone records were submitted showing Richard's phone, missing since the murder, had \"pinged\" off of a Rothesay tower at 6:44 pm on July 6, 2011, after Dennis left Richard's office, and near the location Dennis said he had stopped after visiting his father. A [[Rogers Communications]] analyst, from the cell service provider, testified that the 6:44 pm \"ping\" on July 6, 2011, was the last time Richard's cell phone was seen on the Rogers network. On July 9, 2011, the Rogers Communications computer system received a \"roaming error,\" indicating the phone was not destroyed on July 9.<ref name=\"Unanswered\" />\n\nLeBlanc said that \"quite surprisingly\" Richard's cell phone company had shown Richard's phone to still be functioning 3 days after his murder.<ref name=\"Unanswered\" /> He said he was not satisfied with the cell phone information, saying the records and test calls done by police did not provide sufficient evidence that the phone was \"anywhere near that tower.\" He said \"a jury could conclude Richard Oland's cell phone was outside Canada on July 9.\"<ref name=\"Unanswered\" />\n\nMaureen Adamson, Richard's personal assistant, testified that Dennis had greeted her upon his arrival at the office, where she was preparing to go home for the evening, and that Richard gave Dennis a \"very friendly reception\" at their meeting.<ref name=\"Unanswered\" /><ref name=\"R v Oland 2015\" /> She said Dennis was wearing a brown jacket when visiting his father.<ref name=\"R v Oland 2015\" /> Forensic reports indicated the brown jacket contained 4 microscopic blood drops in the fabric, with DNA matching Richard or Derek.<ref>{{Cite web\n| url = http://live.cbc.ca/Event/Dennis_Oland_second-degree_murder_trial_Nov_24?Page=3\n| title = Dennis Oland second-degree murder trial: Nov. 24\n| website = CBC News\n| access-date = 2016-02-27\n}}</ref>\n\nLeBlanc said that Adamson's testimony \"would allow a jury to conclude as to an absence of animosity.\" The jacket evidence was a bit more confusing for LeBlanc.<ref name=\"Unanswered\" />\n\nThe Crown said the brown jacket was dry cleaned to cover up the murder. The Defence said the jacket was laundered by the wife because the Olands had visitation and funerals to attend, since Dennis's father was deceased.\n\nLeBlanc indicated he felt the police presumed Dennis's guilt too quickly; \"this conclusion on their part was totally unjustified and indeed irrational. The police merely had a hunch, and an unsubstantiated one at that.\" He asked why Dennis would keep a blood-stained jacket, but dispose of the murder weapon and iPhone. He also questioned why Dennis would keep the cleaning tag on after being told he was a suspect, along with the dry-cleaning receipt and his other clothing from the night of the murder did not contain any blood.<ref name=\"Unanswered\" />\n\nHe said Dennis's behaviour after Richard's murder \"appears to be inconsistent with the behaviour expected from someone who committed a crime of extreme violence.\"<ref name=\"Unanswered\" />\n\nLeBlanc agreed that Dennis had the opportunity to kill his father, he had his father's DNA on the brown jacket he was wearing, the brown jacket had been dry cleaned after Dennis was informed he was a suspect, he told the police he was wearing a navy blazer, and there were no signs the murder arose from a robbery or forced entry.<ref name=\"R v Oland 2015\" />\n\nLeBlanc committed Dennis Oland to stand trial, and placed a publication ban over all of the contents of the preliminary inquiry, until after the trial verdict in December 2015.\n\n== Trial and conviction of Dennis Oland ==\n\nJustice Jack Walsh, the former prosecutor in the trial of [[Allan Legere]],  presided over the trial for [[Second degree murder]].<ref>{{Cite web\n| url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/oland-judge-walsh-dna-1.3357233\n| title = Judge at Dennis Oland murder trial is a leading legal expert in DNA\n| website = www.cbc.ca\n| access-date = 2016-02-26\n}}</ref> Walsh reviewed the admissibility of a number of evidence items submitted to the Crown by police prior to the murder trial<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/dennis-oland-preliminary-inquiry-may-hear-from-60-witnesses-1.2652444| access-date = 2018-02-25 |title=Dennis Oland preliminary inquiry may hear from 60 witnesses}}</ref>   \nAs the largest jury pool in New Brunswick history, jury selection was held in the nearby hockey arena.  \nThe case was very highly publicised in the area, with some concerns over the ability to have a [[fair trial]].<ref name=\"by storm\" /><ref name=\"jury selection\">{{Cite web\n| url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/dennis-oland-jury-selection-day-one-1.3215856\n| title = Jury selection in Dennis Oland's murder trial begins in Saint John\n| website = www.cbc.ca\n| access-date = 2016-02-26\n}}</ref>\n\nAbout five thousand prospective jurors were summoned from Saint John and Kings counties.<ref>{{Cite web\n| url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/denis-oland-murder-trial-1.3219329\n| title = Dennis Oland pleads not guilty to 2nd-degree murder\n| website = www.cbc.ca\n| access-date = 2016-02-26\n}}</ref>  16 jurors were empanelled: 12 jurors with 4 alternates.<ref>{{Cite web\n| url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/denis-oland-murder-jury-1.3219942\n| title = Dennis Oland murder trial jury selection almost complete\n| website = www.cbc.ca\n| access-date = 2016-02-27\n}}</ref> Beginning on September 16, 2015, the Dennis Oland trial was the longest in the province's history at 65 days in length.<ref name=\"set to begin\"/>\n\nThe Court excluded a number of items from evidence due to police improprieties, including dishonest applications for search warrants and unlawful search and seizure.<ref name=\"R v Oland 2015\" /><ref>{{Cite web\n| url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/dennis-oland-murder-warrant-charter-1.3357229\n| title = Dennis Oland's charter rights violated by police, judge ruled\n| website = www.cbc.ca\n| access-date = 2016-02-26\n}}</ref>\n\nDennis Oland was convicted of second degree murder in December 2015 and sentenced to life in prison, with no possibility of parole for at least 10 years.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/dennis-oland-sentencing-murder-1.3435552 |title=Dennis Oland gets life in prison for killing father, Richard Oland|last=MacKinnon |first=Bobbi-Jean |date=11 February 2016 |website=CBC News |publisher=CBC |access-date=23 January 2017}}</ref> On July 19 2019, Dennis Oland was found not guilty in a new trial.\n\n== Appeal ==\n\nOn October 24, 2016, the [[New Brunswick Court of Appeal]] overturned Dennis Oland's conviction on the basis that \"the trial judge had erred in his instructions to jury on a 'key piece of the evidential puzzle' \u2014 whether Oland had 'lied' to police about what he was wearing the night they believe his multimillionaire father was killed,\" according to CBC News. The appeals panel ordered a new trial.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/dennis-oland-new-trial-date-murder-1.3918940 |title=Dennis Oland gets new 2nd-degree murder trial, as appeal court cites judge's error|last=MacKinnon |first=Bobbi-Jean  |date=24 October 2016 |website=CBC News |publisher=CBC |access-date=23 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web \n| url = http://news.nationalpost.com/news/canada/dennis-oland-to-be-tried-a-second-time-for-murder-in-2011-death-of-wealthy-new-brunswick-father\n| title = Dennis Oland to be tried a second time for murder in 2011 death of wealthy New Brunswick father\n| website = National Post\n| access-date = 2016-10-24\n}}</ref> Before a new trial was scheduled, the Crown attorneys said they would ask the [[Supreme Court of Canada]] for leave to appeal the ruling; the defense said it might request a full acquittal from the same court.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nationalnewswatch.com/2017/01/03/dennis-oland-expected-in-court-today-in-murder-case-of-multimillionaire-father/#.WIZaMVMrLX4 |title=N.B. Crown to appeal ruling overturning Dennis Oland\u2019s murder conviction |last=Bisset |first=Kevin |date=3 January 2017 |website=National News Watch |publisher=National News Watch |access-date=23 January 2017 |quote=he was surprised the Crown is filing an appeal to the Supreme Court. My understanding is that the other side could then ... appeal on some of the grounds they were denied on in the Court of Appeal in Fredericton}}</ref>\n\n== Aftermath ==\n\nThe Provincial Police Commission launched an investigation into the mishandling of the Oland homicide investigation by the Saint John Police Force after the trial was completed.<ref>{{Cite web\n| url = http://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/former-prosecutor-to-probe-police-handling-of-oland-murder-1.2721868\n| title = Former prosecutor to probe police handling of Oland murder\n| website = Atlantic\n| access-date = 2016-02-27\n}}</ref> Deputy Chief Glen McCloskey was also being investigated for his conduct.<ref>{{Cite web\n| url = https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/new-brunswick-police-commission-to-probe-police-handling-of-oland-murder/article27907784/\n| title = New Brunswick police commission to probe police handling of Oland murder\n| website = The Globe and Mail\n| access-date = 2016-02-27\n}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Maclean's]] magazine, the officers' \"controversially\u2014and almost comically\u2014sloppy sleuths helped to explain the lack of evidence. While working on the crime scene, officers used the bathroom for two days before it could be tested for blood or fingerprints, and they couldn\u2019t always remember what they had touched around the office with bloodied gloves. The blood spatter expert didn\u2019t arrive from Halifax until four days after the homicide, by which time the body had been removed and spatter had dried and flaked. Officers touched the back door before testing it for fingerprints, didn\u2019t interview some witnesses for 18 months, and didn\u2019t photograph the back alleyway until three years after the crime\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.macleans.ca/news/canada/the-oland-murder-trial-that-took-new-brunswick-by-storm/ |title=The murder trial that took New Brunswick by storm |last=Campbell |first=Meagan |date=30 December 2015 |website=Macleans |publisher=Rogers Media |access-date=23 January 2017 |quote=This isn\u2019t the police\u2019s finest hour. Never has the police looked so long to find so little.}}</ref> Deputy Chief Glen McCloskey was cleared after an investigation by Halifax police and he will not be charged with any criminal offence.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/oland-leave-appeal-supreme-court-crown-1.3919290 |title=Crown seeks leave to appeal overturning of Dennis Oland's murder conviction |last=MacKinnon  |first=Bobbi-Jean |date=3 January 2017 |website=CBC News |publisher=CBC |access-date=23 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe [[CBC Television]] documentary series ''[[The Oland Murder]]'', centred on Dennis Oland's appeal and retrial, premiered in 2020.<ref>[[John Doyle (critic)|John Doyle]], [https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/television/article-whodunnit-cbc-hits-the-true-crime-jackpot-with-the-oland-murder/ \"Whodunnit: CBC hits the true-crime jackpot with The Oland Murder\"]. ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', March 2, 2020.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:2011 crimes in Canada]]\n[[Category:2011 in New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Crime in New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:History of Saint John, New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:2010s murders in Canada]]\n[[Category:2011 murders in North America]]\n", "text_old": "The '''homicide of Richard Oland''' occurred on July 7, 2011, when 69-year-old [[Canada|Canadian]] businessman [[Richard Oland]], previously a vice-president with [[Moosehead Brewery]], was bludgeoned to death in his office on Canterbury Street in [[Saint John, New Brunswick|Saint John]], [[New Brunswick]].<ref name=\"car shoes bag\">{{Cite web|title = Dennis Oland's car, shoes, bag all tested negative for blood, jury hears|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/oland-murder-trial-mark-smith-1.3260262|website = www.cbc.ca|access-date = 2016-02-19}}</ref> Oland's son, Dennis, came under suspicion for the killing and was officially charged with [[second degree murder]].<ref name=\"huffpo\">{{cite news|last1=Bissett|first1=Kevin|title=Dennis Oland Charged In Father's Death|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2013/11/13/dennis-oland-murder_n_4266411.html|accessdate=5 July 2014|agency=Associated Press|publisher=Huffington Post|date=2013-11-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Dennis Oland charged with 2nd-degree murder in dad's death|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/dennis-oland-charged-with-2nd-degree-murder-in-dad-s-death-1.2424736|website = www.cbc.ca|access-date = 2016-02-19}}</ref> Dennis Oland's first trial, the longest and most expensive trial in the history of Saint John,<ref name=\"by storm\">{{Cite web|title = How the Oland family murder trial took New Brunswick by storm|url = http://www.macleans.ca/news/canada/the-oland-murder-trial-that-took-new-brunswick-by-storm/|website = Macleans.ca|access-date = 2016-02-19|language = en-US}}</ref> ended with his conviction on December 19, 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Dennis Oland found guilty of second-degree murder|url = https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/dennis-oland-found-guilty-in-murder-of-his-father/article27883485/|website = The Globe and Mail|access-date = 2016-02-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = 'Family tragedy of Shakespearean proportions': Oland gets life for murder|url = http://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/family-tragedy-of-shakespearean-proportions-oland-gets-life-for-murder-1.2773467?autoPlay=true|website = Atlantic|access-date = 2016-02-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Supporters line up as Dennis Oland faces sentencing for murder - Macleans.ca|url = http://www.macleans.ca/news/dennis-oland-faces-sentencing-for-second-degree-murder-in-fathers-death/|website = Macleans.ca|access-date = 2016-02-19|language = en-US}}</ref> Throughout the high-profile court case, intimate details about the private lives of the entire Oland family were revealed.<ref name=\"living hell\">{{Cite web|title = Dennis Oland's mother, Connie, shares 'living hell'|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/dennis-oland-mother-connie-murder-1.3449295|website = www.cbc.ca|access-date = 2016-02-19}}</ref>\n\nDennis Oland was sentenced to [[life imprisonment|life in prison]], with a possibility of [[parole]] in ten years, as recommended by the jury.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/dennis-oland-sentencing-murder-1.3435552|title=Dennis Oland gets life in prison for killing father, Richard Oland|date=11 February 2016|publisher=}}</ref> His lawyers immediately began the [[appeal]]s process, seeking the appellate judges to either overturn the guilty verdict, order a new trial, or enter a full [[acquittal]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = No bail for Dennis Oland as he waits to appeal conviction in father's murder|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/dennis-oland-bail-murder-appeal-1.3450016|website = www.cbc.ca|access-date = 2016-02-19}}</ref> The appeal was successful, and Dennis's conviction was overturned on October 24, 2016. On July 19, 2019, he was found not guilty on retrial.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/dennis-oland-murder-trial-decision-verdict-1.5215559 |title=Dennis Oland not guilty of murder in retrial over 2011 death of multimillionaire father |date= 19 July 2019 |website= CBC News |publisher= CBC |access-date=19 July 2019 |quote= N.B. Court of Queen's Bench Justice Morrison had been deliberating for 10 weeks in 2nd-degree murder trial}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nRichard Oland was the second born son to [[Philip Oland]], chairman and CEO of [[Moosehead Breweries]], and Mary Oland.<ref name=\"Dynasty Macleans\">{{Cite web|title = Murder and a Maritime dynasty: The Dick Oland case - Macleans.ca|url = http://www.macleans.ca/economy/business/murder-and-a-maritime-dynasty-the-dick-oland-case/|website = Macleans.ca|access-date = 2016-02-19|language = en-US}}</ref> Richard and his older brother Derek were born and bred in [[Rothesay, New Brunswick|Rothesay]], [[New Brunswick]], a suburb of [[Saint John, New Brunswick|Saint John]]. Families living within Rothesay, such as the Olands, the [[Irving Oil|Irvings]], and the [[Molasses|Crosbys]], are considered \"old money,\" claiming some of Canada's highest incomes per capita.<ref name=\"Dynasty Macleans\" /> Richard attended Rothesay Collegiate School, Regiopolis College, and the University of New Brunswick, obtaining a certificate of brewing technology.<ref name=\"Dynasty Macleans\" /><ref name=\"Blood, Beer\">{{Cite web|title = Blood, Beer, and the Maritime Rumour Mill: The Dennis Oland Murder Trial   {{!}} VICE {{!}} Canada|url = https://www.vice.com/en_ca/read/blood-beer-and-the-small-town-rumour-mill-the-dennis-oland-murder-trial|website = VICE|access-date = 2016-02-19|language = en-ca}}</ref><ref name=\"funeral home\">{{Cite web|title = Richard Henry Oland - Brenan's Funeral Homes & Crematorium|url = http://www.brenansfh.com/obituaries/63451|website = Brenan's Funeral Homes & Crematorium|access-date = 2016-02-23}}</ref> Richard wed Constance \"Connie\" Connell in 1965,<ref name=\"living hell\" /> and fathered three children: Elizabeth, Jacequeline, and Dennis.<ref name=\"funeral home\" />\n\nBy 1980, Richard, then a vice-president of Moosehead Breweries, vied with Derek for leadership of the company in a public and legal feud. Their father Philip decided to select Derek to succeed him, resulting in Richard leaving the company in 1981.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.macleans.ca/economy/business/murder-and-a-maritime-dynasty-the-dick-oland-case/ |title=Murder and a Maritime dynasty: The Dick Oland case |last=K\u00f6hler |first=Nicholas |date=13 November 2013 |website=Macleans |publisher=Rogers Media |access-date=23 January 2017 |quote=\u201cThe younger one wanted to be president and he hadn\u2019t the experience,\u201d P.W. once told the Financial Post Magazine coolly.}}</ref> Starting from scratch, Richard found a niche in the Saint John business community with his development of three major enterprises - Kinghurst Estates Limited, Brookville Transport Limited, and the [[investment company|investment firm]] Far End Corporation.<ref name=\"living hell\" /> He became an accomplished businessman, amassing many awards and a fortune of nearly [[Canadian dollar|CA$]]37 million.<ref name=\"opens with details\">{{Cite web|title = Oland murder trial opens with details of beating, accused\u2019s financial woes|url = https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/dennis-olands-second-degree-murder-trial-opens-in-new-brunswick/article26377714/|website = The Globe and Mail|access-date = 2016-02-23}}</ref> Oland was also in charge of organizing the 1985 Canada Summer Games.<ref name=\"living hell\"/>\n\nRichard made Far End Corporation's premises his primary office space.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.atlanticbusinessmagazine.net/article/spilled-secrets-the-richard-oland-murder-mystery/ |title=Spilled secrets: the Richard Oland murder mystery |last=Kimber |first=Stephen |date=19 December 2013 |website=Atlantic Business Magazine |publisher=Atlantic Business Magazine |access-date=23 January 2017 |quote=52 Canterbury Street, a refurbished 19th century, three storey, red-brick office building in the heart of historic ... Saint John}}</ref> Located at 52 Canterbury Street in the historic Uptown district of Saint John, the second floor office space was rented from building owner John Ainsworth. Ainsworth operated his own business, Printing Plus, from the first floor of the building, and rented out the third floor to local bands to practice after office hours ended for the day.<ref name=\"mentioned\">{{Cite web|title = How a city councillor ended up being mentioned in the Oland trial|url = https://www.telegraphjournal.com/telegraph-journal/story/45817628/how-a-city-councillor|website = Telegraph-Journal|access-date = 2016-02-19}}</ref> The morning of July 7, 2011, Richard was discovered dead in his office.\n\n== Crime scene ==\nOn July 7, 2011, the body of Richard Oland was discovered lying face down in a pool of blood in his office by his personal assistant, Maureen Adamson.<ref name=\"survived minutes\">{{Cite web|title = Richard Oland survived only 'minutes,' murder trial hears|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/dennis-oland-richard-survived-pathologist-1.3264289|website = www.cbc.ca|access-date = 2016-02-19}}</ref> Sgt. Mark Smith testified that Richard's office was \"one of the bloodiest crime scenes of his career, with the most blows to a victim.\"<ref name=\"car shoes bag\"/> The forensic pathologist, Dr. Ather Naseemuddin, counted forty-five wounds to Richard's hands, neck, and head, during autopsy.<ref name=\"survived minutes\" /><!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Richard Oland's lifeless body.jpg|thumb|274x274px|Richard Oland's body at the crime scene.]] --> Six of these wounds were found on Richard's hands, likely due to Richard trying to protect himself from his attacker.<ref name=\"survived minutes\" /> These [[defensive wound]]s led to over thirty hair and fibre exhibits to be seized at [[autopsy]] for forensic examination, including three hairs found inside Richard's hands and tissue samples from under Richard's fingernails.<ref name=\"Defence evidence\">{{Cite web|title = Defence questions police handling of evidence at Oland trial|url = http://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/defence-questions-police-handling-of-evidence-at-oland-trial-1.2660319|website = Atlantic|access-date = 2016-02-23}}</ref> The hairs could not be tested for DNA as they were lacking a root, and only Richard's DNA was found underneath his fingernails.<ref name=\"Defence evidence\" /><ref name=\"R v Oland 2013\">R. v. Oland, [2013] NBJ 457 (NB CA).</ref>\n\nThe attack continued after Richard was defenseless on the floor.<ref name=\"survived minutes\" /> His skull had suffered catastrophic damage; the bones of his eyesockets were \"like a cracked egg shell,\" possibly from him falling face-first into the floor,<ref name=\"survived minutes\" /> and a concave area spanning 10&nbsp;cm in length, 7&nbsp;cm across, and 2&nbsp;cm deep was discovered at autopsy.<ref name=\"R v Oland 2013\" /> Portions of brain matter were found on Richard's back.<ref name=\"Unanswered\">{{Cite web|title = Questions remain unanswered after Dennis Oland\u2019s trial|url = https://www.telegraphjournal.com/telegraph-journal/story/45891217/questions-remain-unanswered-after|website = Telegraph-Journal|access-date = 2016-02-22}}</ref>\n\nThe attack had left Richard's blood on every single wall of his office.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Dennis Oland murder trial: Oct. 19|url = http://live.cbc.ca/Event/Dennis_Oland_murder_trial_Oct_19?Page=0|website = CBC News|access-date = 2016-02-19}}</ref> Blood spatter was seen on his desk, computer, chair, filing cabinets, and on an empty pizza box in the garbage can.<ref name=\"survived minutes\" /> Blood had also soaked through three layers of flooring, permeating the ceiling of the office below.<ref name=\"Blood, Beer\" /><ref>{{Cite web|title = Trial Hears Dennis Oland Appointed President Of Holding Company After Father's Death {{!}} Country 94 - Saint John, New Brunswick's Best Country Music|url = http://www.country94.ca/news/744206911/trial-hears-dennis-oland-appointed-president-holding-company-after-fathers-death|website = www.country94.ca|access-date = 2016-02-19}}</ref> Police analysts testified \"the person who created these injuries would have significant bloodstains/spatter on their person and would be expected to transfer blood stains to the surfaces of other objects the person came in contact with.\"<ref name=\"R v Oland 2015\">R. v. Oland, [2015] NBJ 312 (NB CA).</ref> Forensic analysts noted the blood pooling on the floor around Richard may not have occurred until after the attacker left the office, explaining why the scene contained few \"transfer stains\" and only one footprint that was never connected to a suspect.<ref name=\"ought to have\">{{Cite web|title = Officers ought to have known how to protect Oland crime scene, trial hears|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/oland-murder-trial-bathroom-1.3258375|website = www.cbc.ca|access-date = 2016-02-22}}</ref>\n\nDr. Matthew Bowes, the physician who reviewed Dr. Nasseemuddin's autopsy report, believed Richard was alive for the duration of the attack.<ref name=\"alive for duration\">{{Cite news|title = Evidence claims Oland was alive for duration of attack.|last = Landry|first = Mike|publisher = New Brunswick Telegraph Journal}}</ref> Both Naseemuddin and Bowes believed he only survived the attack for five to ten minutes<ref name=\"Graphic\">{{Cite web|title = Graphic testimony of Richard Oland\u2019s autopsy heard by Saint John jury Friday|url = http://globalnews.ca/news/2269224/graphic-testimony-of-richard-olands-autopsy-heard-by-saint-john-jury-friday/|website = Global News|access-date = 2016-02-22|first = Heide|last = Pearson}}</ref> but was alive for all of his injuries.<ref name=\"alive for duration\" /> Some injuries were believed to have been caused by a sharp edged weapon, while other injuries were caused by blunt force,<ref name=\"survived minutes\" /> indicating that either Richard was killed by a weapon with two different edges or two weapons were used.<ref name=\"R v Oland 2015\" /> Bowes raised the possibility that a combat knife could have been a weapon.<ref name=\"combat knife\">{{Cite news|title = Combat knife could have been used to kill Oland: expert.|last = Landry|first = Mike|date = Feb 20, 2016|publisher = Telegraph Journal}}</ref> Sgt. Mike King testified that he suspected a roofer's [[hatchet]] to be a weapon.<ref name=\"combat knife\" /> Constable Stephen Davidson believed a weapon could have been a drywall hammer.<ref name=\"drywall hammer\">{{Cite web|title = Dennis Oland murder trial hears suspected weapon was drywall hammer|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/oland-murder-weapon-drywall-hammer-1.3283461|website = www.cbc.ca|access-date = 2016-02-22}}</ref>  No weapons were found at the crime scene, and no weapons were entered as evidence at trial.<ref name=\"drywall hammer\" />\n\nThe trial revealed that members of the Saint John Police Force had failed to protect the crime scene from contamination. Police used the office bathroom, where  blood belonging to the son of Richard's financial manager was later discovered, for two days before the bathroom was tested for evidence.<ref name=\"ought to have\" /> There was a backdoor near where Richard's body was found, leading to an alleyway that could have been an exit.<ref>{{cite book |last=Marquis |first=Greg |date=2016 |title=Truth & Honour. The Death of Richard Oland and the Trial of Dennis Oland. |url=https://www.nimbus.ca/store/truth-and-honour.html?___SID=U |location=Halifax |publisher=Nimbus Publishing |page=22 |isbn=978-1-77108-425-3}}</ref> Police went in and out the main door, without gloves, for nearly a week before anyone noticed they should have tested it for fingerprints.<ref name=\"ought to have\" /> The footprint discovered by the forensics team had to be compared against police footwear, as several police officers, including Deputy Chief Glen McCloskey, walked through the crime scene unauthorized and without protective gear.<ref name=\"ought to have\" /><ref name=\"deputy denies\">{{Cite web|title = Deputy chief denies suggesting officer lie about Richard Oland crime scene|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/dennis-oland-trial-king-police-1.3270115|website = www.cbc.ca|access-date = 2016-02-22}}</ref> McCloskey was later accused of suggesting that other officers [[perjury|lie under oath]] about his presence at the crime scene,<ref name=\"deputy denies\" /> and Saint John Police is currently under investigation by the New Brunswick Police Commission for [[police corruption|corruption]] and a potential cover-up.<ref name=\"Blood, Beer\" /><ref>{{Cite web|title = Saint John police under investigation for how they handled Oland murder|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/oland-investigation-police-commission-1.3376852|website = www.cbc.ca|access-date = 2016-02-22}}</ref>\n\n== Police interviews ==\n\nShortly after being notified of the death, members of the Oland family, including Richard's wife Connie Oland, daughters Lisa Bustin and Jacqueline Walsh, and son Dennis Oland, arrived at the police station to give interviews and formal statements.<ref name=\"living hell\" />\n\nConnie said that on July 6, 2011, she and Richard were both at home until Richard received a call from Maureen Adamson at 9:50 am, reminding him of an appointment in his office with two insurance brokers at 10:00 am.<ref name=\"Order to Rogers\">{{Cite web|url = http://http-server.carleton.ca/~dmckie/Oland%20Production%20Orders.pdf|title = Production Order to Rogers Communications|date = July 9, 2011|publisher = Court of Queen's Bench of New Brunswick|last = Humphrey|first = Stacey}}</ref> Richard then left home for the office, and that was the last time Connie spoke with him. Connie said it was not uncommon for Richard not to return to their residence at night.<ref name=\"Order to Rogers\" />\n\nLisa Bustin, Dennis's sister, was interviewed alone. Bustin said that her father could have had anyone as an enemy, as he was \"a hard-nosed businessman--pure business--and if you worked hard you would get his respect.\"<ref name=\"shed new light\">{{Cite web\n| url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/documents-shed-new-light-on-oland-murder-investigation-1.1699119\n| title = Documents shed new light on Oland murder investigation\n| website = www.cbc.ca\n| access-date = 2016-02-25\n}}</ref>\n\nDennis Oland's interview lasted over five hours and was separate from those of other family members.<ref name=\"living hell\" /> Video footage showed Dennis providing Cst. Stephen Davidson with a written and verbal account of his activities for the day prior, July 6, 2011. He believed that his father had high expectations of him, but that Dennis was not meeting those expectations.\n\nDavidson told Dennis that cameras could verify whether or not he was telling the truth about his presence at his father's office, and asked Dennis what clothing he had worn the day before. Dennis said he was wearing \"these pants, these shoes, a blue dress shirt, and a navy blazer.\"<ref name=\"RAW\">{{Cite web|title = RAW: Dennis Oland's police statement|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/raw-dennis-oland-s-police-statement-1.3283018|website = www.cbc.ca|access-date = 2016-02-19}}</ref>\n\nAt the half-way mark on the video footage, Davidson informed Dennis that he was the primary suspect in his father Richard Oland's murder.<ref name=\"video jury\">{{Cite web|title = Police video jury didn't see shows Dennis Oland being pressured to admit killing father|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/dennis-oland-police-murder-confession-1.3436687|website = www.cbc.ca|access-date = 2016-02-22}}</ref> Davidson read Dennis his rights, and Dennis phoned attorney Bill Teed, who told Dennis to stop talking to police.<ref name=\"video jury\" /> Davidson said \"there is absolutely no question in my mind that you did this, and I want to know why,\" and told Dennis that his opportunity to speak with a lawyer was past. Dennis repeated that he did not murder his father.<ref name=\"video jury\" />\n\nPolice allowed Dennis to leave just after 11:00pm without making an effort to seize the clothes Dennis said he had worn the day before.<ref name=\"Unanswered\" />\n\nRobert McFadden, in his interview, conducted by Cst. Stephen Davidson,<ref name=\"Order to Rogers\" /> said he had left the office at 5:30 pm with his son, Galen McFadden, as was usual.<ref name=\"Order to Rogers\" /> Robert McFadden said his job was to manage Richard's finances, and that Richard had asked that a trust fund be set up for his heirs.<ref name=\"instructions\">{{Cite web|url = http://s3.documentcloud.org/documents/2648059/R-v-Oland-Final-Instructions-Jury-s-Written.txt|title = Judge Walsh's charge to the jury in R. v. Oland|date = December 2015|access-date = February 15, 2016|publisher = The Court of Queen's Bench of New Brunswick|last = Walsh|first = John J.}}</ref> After Richard's death, McFadden said he would run two of Richard's three companies (Kingshurt Estate Ltd and Far End Corporation).<ref name=\"instructions\" /><ref>{{Cite web\n| url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/dennis-oland-murder-director-companies-1.3453441\n| title = Dennis Oland could co-direct murdered father's companies from behind bars\n| website = www.cbc.ca\n| access-date = 2016-02-25\n}}</ref>\n\nMcFadden said that upon Connie's death, the trust would be dissolved, and the remaining assets would be distributed to Richard's three children, Dennis Oland, Jacqueline Walsh, and Lisa Bustin.<ref name=\"instructions\" /> He said that after Connie's death, Dennis's portion of his inheritance would be reduced by $538,000, with $269,000 going to each of Dennis's sisters, covering the expenses of his divorce, which had been paid for by Richard, and allowing Dennis to retain the family home.<ref name=\"instructions\" />\n\nRobert McFadden and Maureen Adamson testified that Richard did not leave the office between arriving in the morning and Maureen leaving at 5:45 PM, and that Richard was adamant that alcohol not be kept in the office.<ref name=\"survived minutes\" /><ref name=\"trial nov 3\">{{Cite web|title = Dennis Oland's second-degree murder trial: Nov. 3|url = http://live.cbc.ca/Event/Dennis_Olands_second-degree_murder_trial_Nov_3?Page=0|website = CBC News|access-date = 2016-02-20}}</ref> Toxicology reports from the medical examiner indicate that Richard had some alcohol in his blood.<ref name=\"Graphic\" />\n\n== Suspects ==\nTwo weeks after the death, police said that they were convinced Richard was murdered by someone he knew.<ref name=\"became suspect\">{{Cite web|title = Dennis Oland became suspect in father's murder same day body was found|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/dennis-oland-murder-statement-1.3281699|website = www.cbc.ca|access-date = 2016-02-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Oland investigation puts Saint John in eerie calm|url = https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/oland-investigation-puts-saint-john-in-eerie-calm/article557442/|website = The Globe and Mail|access-date = 2016-02-23}}</ref>\n\nSince July 2011, the McFaddens have shared information to advance the investigation. In 2012, nearly a year after the murder, Galen McFadden gave a sample of his DNA.<ref name=\"ought to have\" /> Robert McFadden declined to give a DNA sample.<ref name=\"will insurance\">{{Cite web\n| url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/richard-oland-will-insurance-mcfadden-1.3301617\n| title = Richard Oland was considering changing will, life insurance, jury hears\n| website = www.cbc.ca\n| access-date = 2016-02-25\n}}</ref> Forensic testing in 2012 reveal that blood matching the DNA profile of Galen McFadden was found on the curtains of Richard's office,<ref name=\"blood stain expert\">{{Cite web|title = Blood stain expert continues testimony at Oland murder trial|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/dennis-oland-second-degree-murder-oct-16-1.3274034|website = www.cbc.ca|access-date = 2016-02-22}}</ref> in the bathroom sink, and on a paper towel in the bathroom garbage can.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Dennis Oland second-degree murder trial: Nov. 24|url = http://live.cbc.ca/Event/Dennis_Oland_second-degree_murder_trial_Nov_24?Page=2|website = CBC News|access-date = 2016-02-22}}</ref> One year after Galen's blood was found at the crime scene, officers covertly obtained Robert McFadden's DNA from a straw at a restaurant.<ref name=\"will insurance\" /> The police forensics unit concluded the three areas where Galen's blood was found were unrelated to Richard's murder.  No results concerning Robert's DNA were released.\n\n== Forensic analysis ==\nSgt. Mark Smith, head of the forensics unit of the Saint John Police Force, said he spent three days following the July 14, 2011 search of Dennis's home doing a \"very thorough search\" of Dennis's car.<ref name=\"car shoes bag\" />  Ten different areas of the car were swabbed, including the driver's side door inside latch and handle, the trunk release button, the headlight switch, signal light switch, the steering wheel, the emergency brake, and seats of the car.<ref name=\"live.cbc.ca\">{{Cite web\n| url = http://live.cbc.ca/Event/Dennis_Olands_second-degree_murder_trial_Oct_6\n| title = Dennis Oland's second-degree murder trial: Oct. 6\n| website = ScribbleLive Embed\n| access-date = 2016-02-26\n}}</ref> The swabs were sent away on July 21, 2011, for forensic testing at the RCMP crime lab in Nova Scotia, but no blood or DNA was detected through these tests, either.<ref name=\"R v Oland 2015\" /><ref name=\"live.cbc.ca\"/>\n\nSmith did not find blood or DNA in the laces, stitching, or tread of any of the six pairs of shoes seized from Dennis's home, nor in the red reusable grocery bag Dennis had used to carry genealogy books into Richard's office on July 6, 2011.<ref name=\"car shoes bag\" /> Smith didn't find any blood in the keys of Dennis's Blackberry cell phone, and Richard's DNA was not found anywhere on the phone.<ref name=\"car shoes bag\" />\n\nFor four hours on November 9, 2011, and 1 hour on November 17, 2011, Cst. David MacDonald visually inspected Dennis's brown jacket for blood, identifying 5 \"reddish\" spots, invisible to the naked eye, that required testing by the RCMP forensics lab in Nova Scotia.<ref name=\"jacket focus\">{{Cite web|title = Blood on Dennis Oland's jacket focus of murder trial today|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/richard-oland-murder-trial-1.3277845|website = www.cbc.ca|access-date = 2016-02-23}}</ref> The jacket is sent to the RCMP lab on November 25, 2011, after the warrant for police seizure of the jacket had expired. Four spots on the jacket are confirmed to be blood that matches Richard's DNA - two spots on the outside right sleeve of the jacket, one spot on the outside upper left chest of the jacket, and one spot on the outside back bottom hem near the center of the jacket.<ref name=\"officer gloves\">{{Cite web|title = Dennis Oland's brown jacket was handled by officer without gloves|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/oland-trial-jacket-blood-1.3299712|website = www.cbc.ca|access-date = 2016-02-23}}</ref>\n\n==Charges==\nIn November 2013 Dennis Oland was charged with [[Murder|second degree murder]] for the death of his father. Police stated that no one else would be charged.<ref name=huffpo /> Dennis entered a plea of \"not guilty.\" On November 18, 2013, Justice Hugh McLellan of the New Brunswick Court of Queen's Bench granted Dennis bail on a $50,000 surety, paid by Dennis's uncle (Richard's brother) Derek Oland, the executive chairman of Moosehead Breweries.<ref name=\"R v Oland 2013\" /><ref>{{Cite web\n| url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/dennis-oland-murder-appeal-1.3398445\n| title = Dennis Oland, N.B. man found guilty of murdering multimillionaire father, appeals conviction\n| website = www.cbc.ca\n| access-date = 2016-02-26\n}}</ref> Dennis was also ordered to surrender his passport and advise the [[Saint John Police]] if he planned to travel outside of the province.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/dennis-oland-charged-with-murder-in-fathers-death-granted-bail/article15487595/|title=Dennis Oland, charged with murder in father\u2019s death, granted bail|work=The Globe and Mail}}</ref>\n\n== Preliminary inquiry ==\nProvincial court Judge Ronald LeBlanc presided over the preliminary inquiry on December 12, 2014.<ref name=\"set to begin\">{{Cite web\n| url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/dennis-oland-murder-trial-set-to-begin-in-september-take-65-days-1.2936943\n| title = Dennis Oland murder trial set to begin in September, take 65 days\n| website = www.cbc.ca\n| access-date = 2016-02-26\n}}</ref> He referred to the inquiry as a \"screening mechanism\" to review all of the evidence and rule whether or not he felt the case against Dennis Oland was strong enough to warrant a trial. The preliminary inquiry ultimately spanned 37 days.<ref name=\"Unanswered\" /><ref name=\"set to begin\" />\n\nCrown Prosecutor John Henheffer said that Dennis may have had a financial [[b:Canadian Criminal Evidence|motive]] to murder his father, and that Dennis may have asked his father for more money but was denied by Richard, triggering Dennis's murderous rage.<ref name=\"Unanswered\" />\n\nLeBlanc told the Crown they had \"failed to establish a reason for Dennis Oland to kill his father\" as Connie, Richard's wife, received the $37 million inheritance, not Dennis.<ref name=\"Unanswered\" /> He also said the Crown had no evidence showing that Dennis asked for money or that being denied money would cause Dennis to be violent against his father.<ref name=\"Unanswered\" />\n\nCell phone records were submitted showing Richard's phone, missing since the murder, had \"pinged\" off of a Rothesay tower at 6:44 pm on July 6, 2011, after Dennis left Richard's office, and near the location Dennis said he had stopped after visiting his father. A [[Rogers Communications]] analyst, from the cell service provider, testified that the 6:44 pm \"ping\" on July 6, 2011, was the last time Richard's cell phone was seen on the Rogers network. On July 9, 2011, the Rogers Communications computer system received a \"roaming error,\" indicating the phone was not destroyed on July 9.<ref name=\"Unanswered\" />\n\nLeBlanc said that \"quite surprisingly\" Richard's cell phone company had shown Richard's phone to still be functioning 3 days after his murder.<ref name=\"Unanswered\" /> He said he was not satisfied with the cell phone information, saying the records and test calls done by police did not provide sufficient evidence that the phone was \"anywhere near that tower.\" He said \"a jury could conclude Richard Oland's cell phone was outside Canada on July 9.\"<ref name=\"Unanswered\" />\n\nMaureen Adamson, Richard's personal assistant, testified that Dennis had greeted her upon his arrival at the office, where she was preparing to go home for the evening, and that Richard gave Dennis a \"very friendly reception\" at their meeting.<ref name=\"Unanswered\" /><ref name=\"R v Oland 2015\" /> She said Dennis was wearing a brown jacket when visiting his father.<ref name=\"R v Oland 2015\" /> Forensic reports indicated the brown jacket contained 4 microscopic blood drops in the fabric, with DNA matching Richard or Derek.<ref>{{Cite web\n| url = http://live.cbc.ca/Event/Dennis_Oland_second-degree_murder_trial_Nov_24?Page=3\n| title = Dennis Oland second-degree murder trial: Nov. 24\n| website = CBC News\n| access-date = 2016-02-27\n}}</ref>\n\nLeBlanc said that Adamson's testimony \"would allow a jury to conclude as to an absence of animosity.\" The jacket evidence was a bit more confusing for LeBlanc.<ref name=\"Unanswered\" />\n\nThe Crown said the brown jacket was dry cleaned to cover up the murder. The Defence said the jacket was laundered by the wife because the Olands had visitation and funerals to attend, since Dennis's father was deceased.\n\nLeBlanc indicated he felt the police presumed Dennis's guilt too quickly; \"this conclusion on their part was totally unjustified and indeed irrational. The police merely had a hunch, and an unsubstantiated one at that.\" He asked why Dennis would keep a blood-stained jacket, but dispose of the murder weapon and iPhone. He also questioned why Dennis would keep the cleaning tag on after being told he was a suspect, along with the dry-cleaning receipt and his other clothing from the night of the murder did not contain any blood.<ref name=\"Unanswered\" />\n\nHe said Dennis's behaviour after Richard's murder \"appears to be inconsistent with the behaviour expected from someone who committed a crime of extreme violence.\"<ref name=\"Unanswered\" />\n\nLeBlanc agreed that Dennis had the opportunity to kill his father, he had his father's DNA on the brown jacket he was wearing, the brown jacket had been dry cleaned after Dennis was informed he was a suspect, he told the police he was wearing a navy blazer, and there were no signs the murder arose from a robbery or forced entry.<ref name=\"R v Oland 2015\" />\n\nLeBlanc committed Dennis Oland to stand trial, and placed a publication ban over all of the contents of the preliminary inquiry, until after the trial verdict in December 2015.\n\n== Trial and conviction of Dennis Oland ==\n\nJustice Jack Walsh, the former prosecutor in the trial of [[Allan Legere]],  presided over the trial for [[Second degree murder]].<ref>{{Cite web\n| url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/oland-judge-walsh-dna-1.3357233\n| title = Judge at Dennis Oland murder trial is a leading legal expert in DNA\n| website = www.cbc.ca\n| access-date = 2016-02-26\n}}</ref> Walsh reviewed the admissibility of a number of evidence items submitted to the Crown by police prior to the murder trial<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/dennis-oland-preliminary-inquiry-may-hear-from-60-witnesses-1.2652444| access-date = 2018-02-25 |title=Dennis Oland preliminary inquiry may hear from 60 witnesses}}</ref>   \nAs the largest jury pool in New Brunswick history, jury selection was held in the nearby hockey arena.  \nThe case was very highly publicised in the area, with some concerns over the ability to have a [[fair trial]].<ref name=\"by storm\" /><ref name=\"jury selection\">{{Cite web\n| url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/dennis-oland-jury-selection-day-one-1.3215856\n| title = Jury selection in Dennis Oland's murder trial begins in Saint John\n| website = www.cbc.ca\n| access-date = 2016-02-26\n}}</ref>\n\nAbout five thousand prospective jurors were summoned from Saint John and Kings counties.<ref>{{Cite web\n| url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/denis-oland-murder-trial-1.3219329\n| title = Dennis Oland pleads not guilty to 2nd-degree murder\n| website = www.cbc.ca\n| access-date = 2016-02-26\n}}</ref>  16 jurors were empanelled: 12 jurors with 4 alternates.<ref>{{Cite web\n| url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/denis-oland-murder-jury-1.3219942\n| title = Dennis Oland murder trial jury selection almost complete\n| website = www.cbc.ca\n| access-date = 2016-02-27\n}}</ref> Beginning on September 16, 2015, the Dennis Oland trial was the longest in the province's history at 65 days in length.<ref name=\"set to begin\"/>\n\nThe Court excluded a number of items from evidence due to police improprieties, including dishonest applications for search warrants and unlawful search and seizure.<ref name=\"R v Oland 2015\" /><ref>{{Cite web\n| url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/dennis-oland-murder-warrant-charter-1.3357229\n| title = Dennis Oland's charter rights violated by police, judge ruled\n| website = www.cbc.ca\n| access-date = 2016-02-26\n}}</ref>\n\nDennis Oland was convicted of second degree murder in December 2015 and sentenced to life in prison, with no possibility of parole for at least 10 years.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/dennis-oland-sentencing-murder-1.3435552 |title=Dennis Oland gets life in prison for killing father, Richard Oland|last=MacKinnon |first=Bobbi-Jean |date=11 February 2016 |website=CBC News |publisher=CBC |access-date=23 January 2017}}</ref> On July 19 2019, Dennis Oland was found not guilty in a new trial.\n\n== Appeal ==\n\nOn October 24, 2016, the [[New Brunswick Court of Appeal]] overturned Dennis Oland's conviction on the basis that \"the trial judge had erred in his instructions to jury on a 'key piece of the evidential puzzle' \u2014 whether Oland had 'lied' to police about what he was wearing the night they believe his multimillionaire father was killed,\" according to CBC News. The appeals panel ordered a new trial.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/dennis-oland-new-trial-date-murder-1.3918940 |title=Dennis Oland gets new 2nd-degree murder trial, as appeal court cites judge's error|last=MacKinnon |first=Bobbi-Jean  |date=24 October 2016 |website=CBC News |publisher=CBC |access-date=23 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web \n| url = http://news.nationalpost.com/news/canada/dennis-oland-to-be-tried-a-second-time-for-murder-in-2011-death-of-wealthy-new-brunswick-father\n| title = Dennis Oland to be tried a second time for murder in 2011 death of wealthy New Brunswick father\n| website = National Post\n| access-date = 2016-10-24\n}}</ref> Before a new trial was scheduled, the Crown attorneys said they would ask the [[Supreme Court of Canada]] for leave to appeal the ruling; the defense said it might request a full acquittal from the same court.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nationalnewswatch.com/2017/01/03/dennis-oland-expected-in-court-today-in-murder-case-of-multimillionaire-father/#.WIZaMVMrLX4 |title=N.B. Crown to appeal ruling overturning Dennis Oland\u2019s murder conviction |last=Bisset |first=Kevin |date=3 January 2017 |website=National News Watch |publisher=National News Watch |access-date=23 January 2017 |quote=he was surprised the Crown is filing an appeal to the Supreme Court. My understanding is that the other side could then ... appeal on some of the grounds they were denied on in the Court of Appeal in Fredericton}}</ref>\n\n== Aftermath ==\n\nThe Provincial Police Commission launched an investigation into the mishandling of the Oland homicide investigation by the Saint John Police Force after the trial was completed.<ref>{{Cite web\n| url = http://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/former-prosecutor-to-probe-police-handling-of-oland-murder-1.2721868\n| title = Former prosecutor to probe police handling of Oland murder\n| website = Atlantic\n| access-date = 2016-02-27\n}}</ref> Deputy Chief Glen McCloskey was also being investigated for his conduct.<ref>{{Cite web\n| url = https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/new-brunswick-police-commission-to-probe-police-handling-of-oland-murder/article27907784/\n| title = New Brunswick police commission to probe police handling of Oland murder\n| website = The Globe and Mail\n| access-date = 2016-02-27\n}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Maclean's]] magazine, the officers' \"controversially\u2014and almost comically\u2014sloppy sleuths helped to explain the lack of evidence. While working on the crime scene, officers used the bathroom for two days before it could be tested for blood or fingerprints, and they couldn\u2019t always remember what they had touched around the office with bloodied gloves. The blood spatter expert didn\u2019t arrive from Halifax until four days after the homicide, by which time the body had been removed and spatter had dried and flaked. Officers touched the back door before testing it for fingerprints, didn\u2019t interview some witnesses for 18 months, and didn\u2019t photograph the back alleyway until three years after the crime\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.macleans.ca/news/canada/the-oland-murder-trial-that-took-new-brunswick-by-storm/ |title=The murder trial that took New Brunswick by storm |last=Campbell |first=Meagan |date=30 December 2015 |website=Macleans |publisher=Rogers Media |access-date=23 January 2017 |quote=This isn\u2019t the police\u2019s finest hour. Never has the police looked so long to find so little.}}</ref> Deputy Chief Glen McCloskey was cleared after an investigation by Halifax police and he will not be charged with any criminal offence.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/oland-leave-appeal-supreme-court-crown-1.3919290 |title=Crown seeks leave to appeal overturning of Dennis Oland's murder conviction |last=MacKinnon  |first=Bobbi-Jean |date=3 January 2017 |website=CBC News |publisher=CBC |access-date=23 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe [[CBC Television]] documentary series ''[[The Oland Murder]]'', centred on Dennis Oland's appeal and retrial, premiered in 2020.<ref>[[John Doyle (critic)|John Doyle]], [https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/television/article-whodunnit-cbc-hits-the-true-crime-jackpot-with-the-oland-murder/ \"Whodunnit: CBC hits the true-crime jackpot with The Oland Murder\"]. ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', March 2, 2020.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:2011 crimes in Canada]]\n[[Category:2011 in New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Crime in New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:History of Saint John, New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:2010s murders in Canada]]\n[[Category:2011 murders in North America]]\n", "name_user": "OldCityServices", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBackground:changed \"bred\" to \"reared\"  talking about humans growing up not ranching cattle", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homicide_of_Richard_Oland"}
